body:
Yeah, so my use case is actually something like this:

``` rust
enum NS {
    StructNS,
    ValNS,
    TypeNS,
    ModNS,
}

struct Subscope {
    table: SmallIntMap<NS, DefId>,
}

impl Subscope {
    fn new() -> Subscope {
        Subscope { table: SmallIntMap::with_capacity(num_variants::<NS>()) }
    }
}
```

That SmallIntMap could easily be a vector.  It's more useful as a constant than as a slice, and I think a derived trait is far too much for use cases like that, when all you need to know is how many different distinct values you're going to need.

A derived trait is much cleaner than a specialized intrinsic. And being able to derive `Bounded` would produce exactly what you need.

``` rust
let ns: NS = Bounded::max_value();
Subscope { table: SmallIntMap::with_capacity(ns as uint) }
```

@kemurphy Here's what the code would look like with that:

``` rust
#[deriving(Bounded)]
enum NS {
    StructNS = 3, // because maybe it's C compat?
    ValNS,
    TypeNS,
    ModNS,
}

struct Subscope {
    table: SmallIntMap<NS, DefId>,
}

impl Subscope {
    fn new() -> Subscope {
        let (min, max): (NS, NS) = (Bounded::min_value(), Bounded::max_value());
        let count = max as uint - min as uint + 1;
        Subscope { table: SmallIntMap::with_capacity(count) }
    }
}
```

Note that your proposed intrinsic won't handle this case, because the enum now starts at `3`.

@kemurphy 

> there's no AST map available to introspect which variants belong to a given enum.

What do you mean? Of _course_ Deriving knows what variants your enum has. It can't possibly work otherwise! What exactly do you think `#[deriving(Eq)]` is doing? It's not evaluating to

``` rust
impl Eq for Foo {
    fn eq(&self, other: &Foo) -> bool {
        intrinsics::eq(self, other)
    }
}
```

It's evaluating to

``` rust
impl Eq for Foo {
    fn eq(&self, other: &Foo) -> bool {
        match self {
            Foo1 => match other {
                Foo1 => true,
                _ => false
            },
            Foo2 => match other {
                Foo2 => true,
                _ => false
            }
            // ...
        }
    }
}
```

This very clearly knows what the variants are.

@kemurphy 

> Countable being a super-trait of Bounded though is still wrong

Only if `count()` is defined in terms of `Bounded`. I'm suggesting something like

``` rust
pub trait Countable : Bounded {
    fn count() -> uint;
}
```

There could be a default implementation like

``` rust
pub trait Countable : Bounded {
    fn count() -> uint {
        let min: Self = Bounded::min_value();
        let max: Self = Bounded::max_value();
        max - min + 1
    }
}
```

which would then be reimplemented for the types that actually do have holes, but I don't know if that's actually a good idea. It would mean that, for a type without holes, you can implement it using `impl Countable for Foo {}` as long as you already implemented `Bounded`, but whether or not that's a good idea, I can't answer.

The only real issue with `Countable` (besides the fact that it's a once-off trait) is the fact that it cannot be implemented on `uint` or `u64`, because the count would overflow (even if it's defined to return `u64`, this would still be a problem). This is actually why I think it might not be a great idea, and why it might be better simply to have `Bounded` and let you calculate the count yourself (which would only work for types without holes). Alternatively, `Countable` could just not be implemented on the numeric primitives (after all, it's not particularly useful there). But then it would be a libstd trait that has zero implementing types in libstd, which seems pretty odd.

@kemurphy 

> or u64 and i64 both, there are u64::max_value() possible values

Nope, there are `u64::max_value() + 1` possible values. You forgot about `0`. And unfortunately, `u64::max_value() + 1` wraps around to `0`. We'd need a `u128` type for this, except then you'd have the same problem implementing `Countable` for `u128`.

Which is to say, I think there's utility in having the following:

``` rust
// I have no idea what to call this
pub trait Foo {
    fn next_value(&self) -> Option<Self>;
    fn prev_value(&self) -> Option<Self>;
}

pub trait Countable : Foo + Bounded {
    fn count() -> uint; // or maybe u64?
}
```

and to add support for `#[deriving(Bounded,Foo,Countable)]` to C-like enums. Theoretically it can work for non-C-like enums too, as long as every field implements these traits, although that would certainly complicate the expansion.

So, here's why I like the intrinsic:  Say someday the compiler auto-implements the CLike trait for C-like enums -- then we get

``` rust
impl<E: CLike> Countable for E {
    fn count() -> uint { num_variants::<E>() }
}
```

And then we could also provide `#[deriving(Countable)]` for non-C-like enum types that are built on C-like enum types (or any other type that manually derived Countable).  Thoughts?

@alexcrichton I'm curious as to why you think Bounded fits here?  The whole point of this intrinsic is to avoid having to manually count the number of variants in the enum.  It sounds like a `#[deriving(Bounded)]` would get the job done for my use case (albeit with a little ugliness) for C-like enums with no holes, but that solution just doesn't feel like the right answer to me.  Also without the intrinsic there's no other way to reflect on an arbitrary enum like this.

Another use case I thought of earlier involves an enum you have no control over.  This example is a little contrived but I can think of cases like Multiboot 2 request/response tags where it actually may apply.

``` rust
// in another crate
pub struct Shape {
    Circle(uint),
    Rectangle(uint, uint),
    Triangle(uint, uint, uint),
}

// collect the shapes and be ready to hand back by shape
struct ShapeCollector {
    shapes: Vec<Vec<Shape>>
}

impl ShapeCollector {
    fn new() {
        StructCollector {
            shapes: Vec::with_capacity(NUM_SHAPES)
        }
    }
}
```

Here `Bounded` doesn't really make much sense and without an intrinsic or some sort of default impl for all enum types you would need to keep NUM_SHAPES manually in sync with the library.

@kballard 

> Your code already encodes the fact that there are 3 buckets.

Where? The enum is in a crate I don't own.

> Hiding the capacity behind some intrinsic actually serves to make it less obviously correct.

I have to disagree. Using a literal 3 or even `static NUM_SHAPES: uint = 3;` is less obviously correct in my eyes; on the other hand, `num_variants::<Shape>()` looks very clear and tells me exactly what I'm getting.

@thestinger I don't think I'm familiar with the function merging issue, is there an issue/RFC/PR or something you can throw at me for context?

@kemurphy I really don't like the idea of automatically deriving traits for types without being asked to. Why is `num_variants()` special enough that it should be derived for all C-like enums but e.g. `Eq` is not?

As for your example code, I still disagree that `num_variants()` is wrong. Using `num_variants()` to fill the capacity makes the implicit assumption that the number of buckets used elsewhere in the code is equal to the number of variants, but the code elsewhere does not make that assumption explicit. Nor do I trust that the rest of the code is even making that particular assumption. What if a `Square(uint)` variant is added, but the `ShapeCollector` decides that `Square`s are actually just a special case of `Rectangle`? You'd have 4 variants but `ShapeCollector` would still only be using 3 buckets.

Basically, what I'm trying to say is that `ShapeCollector` needs to map each `Shape` to some other type to use as the bucket key. For example, a `uint`. It can't just use the variant directly because you can have multiple `Circle`s that are distinct (because of the variant fields). The place where this mapping of `Shape -> uint` is performed is what defines how many buckets there are (and it does so by defining how many unique `uint` values it produces). That place is what should also explicitly provide the number of buckets, which makes your code look like

``` rust
impl ShapeCollector {
    fn new() {
        ShapeCollector {
            shapes: Vec::with_capacity(ShapeCollector::num_buckets())
        }
    }
}
```

And `ShapeCollector::num_buckets()` has no reason to use `num_variants()`.

Or to be even more explicit, maybe it doesn't map it to `uint` but instead it maps it to your own

``` rust
#[deriving(Countable)]
enum ShapeBucket {
    CircleBucket,
    RectangleBucket,
    TriangleBucket
}
```

which lets you use `#[deriving]` all you want.

@kballard: I mean honestly I think `Eq` should be too, but that's a question for the core developers, not me.

As for the `ShapeBucket` thing, I see your point there.  That does make more sense.

.... But we could argue about tasteful use cases all day -- I'd rather at this point just focus on discussion of this particular patch, which aims to solve a reflection problem that is otherwise unsolvable.  At this point you've expressed your opinion that you find it undesirable; I respect that, but it would be nice if we could un-derail this discussion and get back to constructive feedback.  I would like to see what the rest of the interested parties have to say.

@dobkeratops: rust makes no guarantees about the layout of an enum at runtime, but perhaps a special TaggedUnion deriving would be handy.

A while back I proposed syntax like the following, but nobody seemed to think it was a good idea:

``` rust
enum CCompatTaggedUnion {
    Tag1 { data: *u8, len: uint } = TAG1_DISR,
    Tag2 { data: u32 } = TAG2_DISR,
    // ...
}
```

Perhaps something like that or a `#[disr=TAG1_DISR]` attribute or something would be useful in tandem with a TaggedUnion trait?  I'm bikeshedding here and it really isn't relevant to this PR but yeah.

@kemurphy What is your opposition to "implement `#[deriving(Bounded)]`"? Do you truly feel that saying

``` rust
let max: MyEnum = Bounded::max_value();
let min: MyEnum = Bounded::min_value();
let count = max as uint - min as uint + 1;
```

is not a workable solution? I expect that implementing `#[deriving(Bounded)]` is non-controversial (for C-like enums at least, though non-C-like would work if all fields implement `Bounded` too). And once it's done, then adding my proposed `.next_value()`/`.prev_value()` trait or the `Countable` trait will make more sense.

As a side note, if we do implement `#[deriving(Bounded)]` then I think at least the description has to change. Right now it explicitly refers to numbers, but this would generalize it to values that have an upper and lower bound.

@kballard: My opposition is that this is not a bounds problem, it is simply a number of variants problem.  It doesn't typecheck, one might say. :)

``` rust
let max: MyEnum = Bounded::max_value();
let min: MyEnum = Bounded::min_value();
let count = max as uint - min as uint + 1;
```

While this works for my particular use case, in my opinion it is very unwieldy and overly complex.  Deriving Bounded also does not work for C-like enums with holes in them, for 2 reasons:
- You lose the ability to count the variants unless you know where the holes are.
- Bounded implies the type can take any value between min and max, whereas an enum with holes only takes a subset of those.

Also, generally, deriving Bounded for an enum to me would imply that you could take any old `uint` and {interpret it as,cast it to} that enum and have things Just Work, which a) violates type safety more than I think is acceptable, and b) also falls apart for enums with holes.  Plus the whole fact that the description of Bounded would have to change.  It just sounds like an incorrect approach overall to me.

Associated values is the real solution here, so you can just say `Foo::NUM_VALUES`. But we don't support that. (I believe this associated value would still need to be `#[derive(..)]`d, presumably by declaring it on some trait).

Until such time as we get associated values, I think trying to emit a static is a bad API.

So right now, I think the best solution is the trait that returns `&[T]`. But the question of naming is a tough one. Maybe something like

``` rust
pub trait EnumValues {
    fn enum_values() -> &'static [Self];
}
```

Although since this only works for C-like enums, it would be nice to put `CLike` in the name. But I think `CLikeEnumValues` is just a bit too unwieldy.

``` rust
pub trait Discrete {
    pub fn domain() -> &'static [Self]; // or pub fn values()
}
```

Hm, yeah Discrete probably isn't the right word  I was looking for something like Finite, I guess?  With Discrete I was thinking like "discrete set of values"; the integral types also apply but in that case the trait would look more like 

``` rust
pub trait Discrete {
    pub fn values<T:Iterator>() -> T<Self>;
}
```

``` rust
pub trait Enumerable {
    fn values() -> &'static Self;
    fn iter<T: Iterator>() -> T<Self>;
}
```

That `iter()` function doesn't work. We don't have higher-kinded types. You'd have to say

``` rust
pub trait Enumerable<T: Iterator<Self>> {
    fn values() -> &'static Self;
    fn iter() -> T;
}
```

and then the implementation would have to provide the concrete iterator type.

I don't think this is worthwhile. The same iterator can be accomplished just by calling `.iter().map(|&x| x)` on the result of `values()`.
